## save state names in this table for later use
state = readxl::read_excel("./data/State_to_State_Migrations_Table_2018.xls", skip = 4, n_max=3, col_names = FALSE)
## New names:
## * `` -> ...1
## * `` -> ...2
## * `` -> ...3
## * `` -> ...4
## * `` -> ...5
## *  and 125 more problems
# filter out useful columns
state = data.frame(t(rbind(state, colnames(state))))  # X1 X2 X3 X4
state = state %>% filter(!is.na(X2) & X2 != 'Total') # state name
state = state %>% slice(c(1:52)) # drop 'U.S. Island Area' and 'Foreign Country' at the end
state = subset(state, select = -c(X1, X3)) # drop columns
# column indexs with state data
columns = state$X4 %>% as.vector
columns = c("...1", columns)
## fulldf contains the full migration data with rows = current and cols = before
# read in dataset
fulldf = readxl::read_excel("./data/State_to_State_Migrations_Table_2018.xls", skip = 4, col_names = FALSE)
## New names:
## * `` -> ...1
## * `` -> ...2
## * `` -> ...3
## * `` -> ...4
## * `` -> ...5
## *  and 125 more problems
fulldf = fulldf %>% select(columns) %>% # colomns corresponding to migrantion data
         setnames(old = as.vector(state$X4), as.vector(state$X2)) %>% # rename columns to the corresponding state name
         drop_na("...1") %>% # drop empty rows
         slice(3:29, 31:55) # remove useless information

library(tibble)
fulldf = fulldf %>% column_to_rownames('...1') # rename rows to the corresponding state name
fulldf[fulldf == "N/A"] = 0 # covert na to 0
## df contains the requested 3 columns: source, target and count
df = data.frame(reshape2::melt(as.matrix(fulldf), value.name = "count", varnames = c('target', 'source')))
df = df[,c("source", "target", "count")]
## filter out data from NY, TX and two select states
# select these four states as origin states
selected = df[df$source %in% c("New York", "Texas", "Michigan", "Wisconsin"),]

# find top 10 destination states
selected = selected %>% group_by(source) %>%
     arrange(count, .by_group = TRUE) %>%
     top_n(10)
## Selecting by count
# convert all state names to abbreviations for convenience
selected$target = state.abb[match(selected$target, state.name)]
selected$source = state.abb[match(selected$source, state.name)]
circos.clear()
states = c('MI', 'NY', 'TX', 'WI', 'AK', 'AL', 'AZ', 'CA', 'CO', 'CT', 'FL', 'IL', 'IN', 'KS', 'KY', 'MA', 'MD', 'MI', 'MS', 'MT', 'NE', 'NH', 'NJ', 'NM', 'OH', 'PA', 'RI', 'TX', 'UT', 'WA', 'WV')
color = c(MI = 'maroon2', NY = 'slateblue1', TX = 'khaki2', WI = 'lightgreen', AK = 'yellow', AL = 'yellow3', AZ = 'yellow4', CA = 'violet', CO = 'violetred', CT = 'violetred1', FL = 'tomato2', IL = 'steelblue', IN = 'steelblue2', KS = 'springgreen', KY = 'springgreen4', MA = 'royalblue', MD = 'royalblue4', MI = 'royalblue1', MS = 'orange', MT = 'orange3', NE = 'navy', NH = 'olivedrab', NJ = 'pink', NM = 'peru', OH = 'palegoldenrod', PA = 'sienna', RI = 'sienna1', TX = 'sienna2', UT = 'palegreen', WA = 'palegreen4', WV = 'mediumpurple4')

chordDiagram(selected, order = states, grid.col = color,
             annotationTrack = c("name", "grid"),
             annotationTrackHeight = c(0.03, 0.01), transparency = 0.3, big.gap = 10)
title("Network Graph of Migrations from NY, TX, MI and WI", cex = 0.8)
